            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Rivera-Jones is a product of San Francisco\u2019s creative confluence. He was raised in the Inner Sunset by his parents, Sofia Rivera, a celebrated Mission District muralist, and David Jones, a British-born architectural historian. Their home was a lively intersection of cultures, filled with the smell of his mother\u2019s pozole, the sound of his father\u2019s classic rock records, and walls covered in sketches and blueprints. From a young age, Mateo didn\u2019t just see art; he lived within its creation, absorbing the stories behind every brushstroke and building facade.\n\nThis upbringing led him naturally to study Art History at San Francisco State University. While his peers dreamed of curating shows at SFMOMA, Mateo had a quiet revelation during a lackluster internship spent writing wall text. He found himself drawn to the installation crew, the people physically engaging with the art. A turning point came when he helped uncrate a massive Kehinde Wiley painting; the weight, the precision, and the intimate proximity to the masterpiece felt more profound than any academic paper he had ever written.\n\nUpon graduating, Mateo secured a position as an art handler for a firm that services SoMa galleries and private collectors in Pacific Heights. His days are a study in contrasts: carefully maneuvering a priceless sculpture through a pristine gallery one moment, then navigating traffic on his fixed-gear bike the next. His $62,000 salary necessitates a shared apartment in the Mission, just blocks from where his mother painted her first mural. He thrives in the neighborhood's vibrant energy, a stark difference from his quiet Sunset childhood.\n\nHis routine is simple: a morning coffee from a local panaderia, the 2.5-mile bike ride to work, and evenings spent with a close-knit group of friends from college, often sharing burritos in Dolores Park or catching a show at The Fillmore. Mateo\u2019s dream isn\u2019t to be in the spotlight but to be the best in his specialized craft. He aspires to become the head preparator at a major museum, the trusted hand responsible for safeguarding the city\u2019s artistic treasures. For Mateo, San Francisco isn't just a place to live; it\u2019s the canvas, the medium, and the gallery of his life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, sitting on a paint-splattered drop cloth on 24th Street. His mother, Sofia, was sketching a new mural, her hands covered in charcoal. His father, David, knelt beside him, pointing not at the new art, but at the building\u2019s old cornices, explaining their Victorian history. In that moment, the wall became a conversation between past and present. It taught Mateo that every canvas has a story, a truth that became the foundation of how he sees the world.\n\n2.\nAt sixteen, he rode his new fixed-gear bike from the Inner Sunset to the Mission for the first time. He vividly recalls the physical shift\u2014the fog yielding to sharp sunlight, the quiet streets erupting into a symphony of music and voices. It wasn't just a ride; it was a revelation of the city's texture. That day, he learned to read San Francisco not as a map of districts, but as a single, flowing composition, a lesson he carries in his legs on every commute.\n\n3.\nHe was twenty-one, an intern at the museum, dwarfed by a massive Kehinde Wiley painting in the loading bay. As he helped guide the crate, his gloved hands felt the solid, sacred weight of the piece. The scent of oil paint and wood filled the air. Locking eyes with the figure in the portrait, he felt a jolt of profound responsibility that no textbook had ever given him. Art stopped being an academic subject and became a physical, precious object that needed a guardian.\n\n4.\nJust last summer, sitting on the grass in Dolores Park with his friends, sharing a burrito as the sun set. He could see the skyline on one side and, just a few blocks in the other direction, the faded colors of his mother's first public mural. It was a moment of profound rightness, of feeling completely at home. He wasn\u2019t just living in the neighborhood of his family\u2019s history; he was finally building his own life within its vibrant, welcoming arms.\n\n5.\nSix months ago, installing a fragile sculpture in a hushed SoMa gallery. The piece had to be suspended by wires, and the measurements were precise to the millimeter. He remembers holding his breath, his world shrinking to the space between his fingertips and the delicate art. After the final, silent click of the clasp, the curator exhaled in relief. For Mateo, it wasn't about the applause but that quiet, internal hum of perfect execution. It solidified his ambition to master the invisible craft of protection."
